<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-11-17T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-11-17T14:00:00-05:00" n="756" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d756">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94111/93: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-17T19:00:00+00:00">November 17, 1937—7
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 17—4:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1621. I was told at the Foreign Office this afternoon that the report
                                that the Japanese Government had sent some sort of “ultimatum” to
                                the French Government regarding the shipment of munitions through
                                Indo-China to China is entirely untrue. The situation remains that
                                munitions ordered prior to July are permitted to transit Indo-China;
                                the Japanese know this and are displeased; but there has been
                                nothing in the nature of an “ultimatum”.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to American delegation.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>